\begin_layout Section*

\size small
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
A conventional utility analysis depends on price information.
 When observed, the prices embody how the market evaluates the needs of
 the consumers when subjected to supply pressures and how it makes available
 several quality variants that may be substituted for the same purpose by
 the consumer.
 We enrich the typical utility analysis that is based on prices to include
 the quality variation and the needs faced by the consumer in order to study
 the effect of income and the position in social hierarchy on quality consumed
 across multiple commodity groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Here, the needs of the consumers can be proxied with the number of members
 (age-adjusted) in the household (and possibly other available scales) while
 quality can be measured as the portion of budget spent on high vs low-price
 items.
 Using the AIDS model
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonMuellbauerAIDS"

\end_inset

 with this simple formulation, the measures of needs can appear as the control
 variables in the AIDS budget share equations while the quality-choices
 could appear as dependent variables (along with budget share).
 This is McKelvey's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Unrestricted Method
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"

\end_inset

 which we explore in the current chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
While the unrestricted method allows us to explain differences in quality
 in consumer choice, it is neither sufficient to demonstrate the substitution
 between assets purchased and quality demanded nor the discrete choices
 that a consumer faces on less available items (such as electricity in Tanzania).
 As our wider goal is to use the intertemporal substitution setting to understan
d conspicuous consumption, we hope that the measurement of the extent to
 which consumers may choose to save for future rather than overspend on
 higher quality in the current time period subject to their needs could
 help us employ the utility framework under uncertainty that has been explored
 in great detail in the literature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
As a first step towards that purpose, we use a selection equation approach
 to the conventional AIDS formulation to understanding quality for food
 and non-food items in the current chapter.
 We then motivate an exploration of the discrete choice models for uncertainty
 and the gaps in quality that arise out of observed inequalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*

\size small
Literature Survey
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
In the past decades, Deaton's AIDS methodology has been widely used for
 its elegance and clarity.
 Based on PIGL approaches originally popularised by Barten
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BartenPreferences"

\end_inset

, Gorman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GormanPreference"

\end_inset

 and Muellbauer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerAggConsum"

\end_inset

), the method is simple to implement and yet readily conforms to the demand
 function restrictions.
 Still, an AIDS implementations - like any other demand studies - are often
 ailed by the lack of observed market prices.
 This is a limitation that can result in severe measurement errors (see
 Gibson
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GibsonKimQualityBog2019"

\end_inset

 for a discussion).
 The approach that is used quite often is to stick the implicit price-deflator
 (or unit-values) as prices in the AIDS regressions (see Tafere et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TafereTaffesseEthiopia2010"

\end_inset

 for a recent example).
 While this may be the best way to proceed when market price are not observed,
 their use can result in a severe measurement error since the quantities
 consumed by the consumer appear both in the dependent variable (as budget
 share's numerator) in the AIDS regression (see Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wessells_aids"

\end_inset

) and in the control variable (as the denominator for unit-value used as
 price).
 Since observing market prices prevents such measurements errors (see the
 discussion by McKelvey 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"

\end_inset

 and Gibson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GibsonKimQualityBog2019"

\end_inset

), we prefer the methods for understanding quality that use market-observed
 prices over those that use the unit values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
That is not to say that the lack of the market prices in the surveys makes
 the AIDS methodology unusable - only that the correction of such measurement
 errors may not be always trivial (see Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,DeatonSurveyElasticities"

\end_inset

for one such approach and McKelvey
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"

\end_inset

 assessment of the Deaton method).
 It would be fair to say that the extension of AIDS for other panel data
 scenarios is relatively easier.
 For example, the demographic variables in the AIDS model can be accommodated
 with the so-called demographic translation where the intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\alpha_{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{n}\gamma_{ij}ln(p_{jh})+\beta_{i}ln(\frac{x_{h}}{P})$
\end_inset

 is expanded as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\alpha_{i} & =\rho_{io}+\sum_{k=1}^{s}\rho_{ik}d_{k}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[1,n]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{k}$
\end_inset

 are the demographic variables (see Pollack and Wales 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PollockWalesDemand"

\end_inset

).
 Similarly, the structural changes in the parameters over time is addressed
 with a dynamic AIDS formulation that is often based on differencing the
 budget shares over the time-periods (see Anderson Blundell 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "AndersonBlundellAIDSTest1983,AndersonBlundellDynEqn1982"

\end_inset

 for a first-order dynamic model).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Heien and Wessells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HeienWessellsAIDSCensored1990"

\end_inset

 adjust AIDS to account for cases when there is no consumption on certain
 items - by incorporating an inverse Mills ratio into the AIDS regressions.
 This approach is particularly relevant for the analysis of quality since
 the consumption on high quality goods is often 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

truncated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for a significant part of the population.
 This approach performs a first-stage probit where the dependent variable
 is an indicator variable - denoting whether the household 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 consumes the item 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (given 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 demographic variables) or not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
Y_{ih} & =f(p_{1h},p_{2h},...,p_{nh},m_{h},d_{1h},d_{2h},...d_{sh})\label{eq:wessells_probit}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
The inverse mills ratio is thus calculated for every household using the
 probit regression equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wessells_probit"

\end_inset

.
 This ratio i.e.
 the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{ih}=\begin{cases}
\frac{\phi(p_{h},m_{h},d_{h})}{\Phi(p_{h},m_{h},d_{h})} & q_{ih}>0\\
\frac{\phi(p_{h},m_{h},d_{h})}{1-\Phi(p_{h},m_{h},d_{h})} & q_{ih}=0
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

 is used as an instrument in following equation (second stage) to estimate
 the item-elasticities as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
w & =\rho_{io}+\sum_{k=1}^{s}\rho_{ik}d_{kh}+\sum_{j=1}^{n}\gamma_{ij}ln(p_{jh})+\beta_{i}ln(\frac{x_{h}}{P})+\delta_{i}R_{ih}\label{eq:wessells_aids}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Here, we typically have 
\begin_inset Formula $ln(P)=\alpha_{0}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\alpha_{i}ln(p_{i})+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\gamma_{ij}ln(p_{i})ln(p_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 However, a simpler linear-AIDS formulation is often used so that 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}ln(p_{ih})$
\end_inset

 (the Stone's index).
 Notice that the inverse-mills instrument must also comply with the symmetry
 and homogeneity-restrictions and thus one must ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=0}^{n}\delta_{i}R_{ih}=0$
\end_inset

 in addition to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\alpha_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}\gamma_{ij}=0\forall j\in[1,n]$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{n}\beta_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ij}=\gamma_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 Heien-Wessells implementation choose a more general approach for the instrument
 variable by adding an equation to the system with term 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{i}R_{ih}$
\end_inset

 is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\delta_{i}R_{ih}$
\end_inset

so that the additivity condition is always met.
 Unfortunately, the implementation also suffers with the lack of market
 prices - which is probably made worse by having to stick in unit-values
 obtained consumers' using an item on to for those who don't consume the
 item.
 This is needed because the price simply isn't available when the indicator
 variable is zero i.e.
 when the consumers don't consumer an item
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
In fact, Heien-Wessells use a regression with unit-values obtained from
 users who do consume the item as the dependent variable and with control
 variables as their region, income etc.
 .
 The values thus obtained are used as price for the consumers who don't
 consume the item.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Deaton method
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation"

\end_inset

 gets around the price-deflator (unit-value) issues by using the cluster-average
s fitted budget shares and unit-values (which are used instead of the unobserved
 prices).
 Even though Deaton uses these methods for a cross-sectional analysis, the
 intuition can be easily extended to panel data (see McKelvey 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"

\end_inset

 for this extension).
 We note that the so-called RDMP (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 deviations from regional/quarterly mean prices) approach (see Cox-Wohlgenant
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CoxWohlgenant1986"

\end_inset

) - used for studying quality variation in commodities when market prices
 are not available - would also suffer with this issue of measurement error
 (see Gibson and Kim 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GibsonKimQualityBog2019"

\end_inset

 for further details).
 
\end_layout

