\begin_layout Standard

\size small
As noted before, out of the food, energy, transport and household commodity
 groups, we only consider quality differences in food and energy subgroups
 - whereas the other commodity groups are viewed as groups where asset possessio
n (or ownership of long-term durable goods) matters more than quality variation.
 As we further explain, prices observed in the market are of key importance
 to our measure of quality.
 Further, since we don't use price-deflators in our analysis (due the measuremen
t errors that arise with quantity being in both in the denominator of the
 control variables and in the numerator of the dependent variable), these
 observed prices are also of importance to a discussion on cross-price effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
LSMS Tanzania surveys records the prices observed in the markets spread
 across all regions in the country.
 These prices are available for both food and energy commodity groups.
 We group the items within these commodities according to the relative structure
 of the price time-series observed from 2008 to 2014 (see McKelvey
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"

\end_inset

 for a similar analysis of rice varieties).
 The prices observed are shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:LSMSMarketPrices"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Here is a list issues that were observed in the available price data as
 well as the solutions adopted to address them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\size small
A lot of items were recorded with the unit as pieces/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

idadi
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 5 pieces of chicken or 4 pieces of banana etc.).
 For year 2008, there are 588 observations that record prices in terms of
 pieces.
 Since it is difficult to associate a physical measure to a piece, the year
 2008 was removed from our analysis
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
These items were : maize_green, bread, bunscakes, pasta, cassava_fresh,
 cassava_flour, sweet_potato, yam, potatoes, banana_green, othervegstarch,
 pulses, peanuts, coconut, onion, greens, dried_canned_veg, banana_ripe,
 citrus, mangoes, sugarcane, goat, beef, chicken, eggs, fish_seafood, dried_cann
ed_fish, fresh_milk, canned_milk, firewood, cooking_oil, salt, brews, kerosene
 and charcoal.
 The use of pieces, however, has been discouraged since 2008.
 For 2010, we only see the prices on bread, banana_ripe, goat, beef, chicken,
 eggs and fresh_milk items where they are recorded in pieces.
 These price recording are ignored for our analysis.
 In 2012, the items where pieces are used are limited to - bunscakes, goat,
 chicken, eggs and fish_seafood.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Also, 2008 is just too far back for us to use the 2010 household and transport
 CPI baskets as well as the available electricity prices, thus skipping
 the 2008 data is not as serious a concern.
 That said, we do use the 2008 prices for when the units recorded are not
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pieces
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in order to determine the price-structure that aids the classification
 of food groups (with similar price-structure).
 See Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:LSMSMarketPrices"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\size small
A few outlier price observations are rejected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\size small
While a household in the LSMS consumption data is identified down to the
 village and enumeration area level - we do not expect the surveys to record
 market-prices at every possible enumeration area and village.
 We thus associate a district level price to a household's consumed item.
 In other words, the price of an item consumed by a household is linked
 to all households in the same district where the household is located.
 Indeed we make no attempts to arrive at a price granularity lower than
 that of a district.
 When there are multiple price observations at the district level, we arrive
 a district-level price using a regression (discussed below).
 Fruther, when the prices are not available at the district levels, we use
 the regional averages (i.e.
 the next level of granularity available).
 For items such as electricity and gas that are limited to a few urban areas,
 we simply use the price at a national level (see Peng at al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PengElectricityTNZ2016"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
We now describe the regression of marked-price against quantity that we
 use to assimilate the price data from the survey.
 To explain this regression, let's consider an example of the marked prices
 of rice (let's say) for 1 kg, 2kg, 5kg and 10kg in the market.
 A typical set of marked prices could be 4£, 7.5£, 18£ and 35£ respectively.
 The plot would thus look like the one in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:markedprices"

\end_inset

.
 As if often the case, such unit-prices grow at a less than linear rate
 as is shown in the plot of the unit-price corresponding to the quantities
 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:unitprice"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore a linear regression of 
\begin_inset Formula $mp$
\end_inset

 vs 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $mp$
\end_inset

 is the marked price of the item and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 the quantity consumed) is hardly appropriate.
 The goal of the regression is to arrive at the price of unit-quantity (e.g.
 the price per kg for rice in the current example) rather than matching
 the appropriate marked price with the quantity purchased by the consumer
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
If we were to really look for a perfect match for prices, then we should
 not only match the quantities consumed by the consumer with the prices
 recorded in the market but also the time of the household interview with
 that of the price recorded.
 Not only is this fine matching somewhat impractical ( survey prices are
 hardly available at such fine levels of granularity ), it is largely unnecessar
y since our view of price is that of a value that is faced by a sufficiently
 large number of consumers in the survey.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The regression we use therefore is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{mp}{q}=\beta\frac{1}{q^{2}}+c$
\end_inset

 (assuming that the marked price is lower than a linear increase - see Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:markedprices"

\end_inset

 - by a factor that itself decreases with increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $mp=aq-b/q$
\end_inset

).
 Since we use the price set 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset

, the price to be used is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta+c$
\end_inset

 for the regression: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{mp}{q}=\beta/q^{2}+c$
\end_inset

.
 The regression is run only when more than two prices are available.
 When the regression can't be used a simple median is used as the price
 for such cases
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
This does not happen as frequently as one may imagine.
 For 2010, only 9 identified regions for just 6 items have less than three
 marked-prices available.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The price-inference is therefore a 2-stage process - we first obtain prices
 for every district with the regression method.
 If there are no marked prices available in a district, we use the regional
 value of the price.
 For some items, the region-prices are not available for some regions.
 Here, the price from obtained by the regressions over the country is used
 for the item.
 The prices for some items whose consumption is relatively rare in the diary
 data e.g.
 wild-birds and honey are not available for any of the regions.
 These items (~8% price entries) are ignored for the analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
With the prices we obtain after the regression, we match the price for every
 commodity consumed by the household based on the district it is located
 in.
 The next step is to define the groups based on price-structure.
 We use a broad classification of items for separability assumption to hold.
 Within foods we observe protein, fruits, dense-foods, alcohol, complements,
 fresh and non-fresh groups and within energy, we put kerosene and electricity
 under the same group (energy).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
One can argue that a selection bias is introduced when we the national-averages
 for some items and region averages for other.
 This could be a problem if the unavailability of regional averages occurred
 for a significant portion of price entries.
 However, since only about ~4% of the total price observations have no regional
 averages, the bias thus introduced would be rather insignificant.
 Another issue could be taken with our grouping of commodities - as it relies
 on the annual time-series data.
 It is indeed possible that the price of some items may be more volatile
 than the others - and thus the volatility being ignored in the annual time
 series data would bring some bias.
 However, since we combine the household log diary with the recall diary
 (which is recorded on a monthly or yearly basis), a finer time-series for
 prices is not enough to address this issue.
 Such a bias can be alleviated only through finer price data 
\shape italic
and 
\shape default
finer as well as uniformly collected household consumption data.
\end_layout

