\begin_layout Section*

\size small
Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
An analysis of substitution between quality is not complete without establishing
 what quality means in every category.
 Our view of quality is essentially price-based - a consumer who buys more
 of the high-priced item is seen as consuming higher quality.
 This view allows us to see how the demand for quality is distributed across
 the population and varies in response to prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
The framework often used for analysis of quality treats it as if it were
 a real item in the market.
 As for any other item, therefore, the demand for quality must conform to
 the usual demand restrictions i.e.
 the conditions of homogeneity, adding up and non-negativity of the Slutsky
 matrix.
 Since we treat quality as if it were any other item, it could be tempting
 to argue that a consumer observes a price for quality and that the price
 of quality must appear in the econometric analysis.
 However, as we later explain, the price of quality uniquely corresponds
 to the price of the commodity aggregate and the relative-price structure.
 The two implicitly determine what one may consider the price of quality.
 The step of preparing a composite however, comes at a cost - as the aggregation
 needs to satisfy a few conditions in addition to the usual restrictions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Before we describe how quality is measured for our purposes in the current
 chapter, we survey a few approaches towards quality measurement that have
 been used in the literature.
 To avoid confusion of terms in our discussion on quality, we use the nomenclatu
re provided by Cramer
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CramerIncomePrice1973"

\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

goods
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are variants with different quality that all fall under a certain 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

commodity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (also see Cox
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CoxWohlgenant1986"

\end_inset

 for the notes on this nomenclature).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
The simplest of these approaches is to view the demand for a high-quality
 item as more of the low-cost item.
 This approach strives to obtain an adjustment factor for the demand based
 on the consumption on items (see Griliches 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GrilichesIndex1971"

\end_inset

 for the theoretical underpinnings with the approach and with measurement
 of quality change).
 A formulation more relevant to our approach is provided by Houthakker 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

 and Deaton
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,DeatonEconConsumer"

\end_inset

 where quality is viewed as a separate commodity.
 Here, the quantities consumed for two (or more) items within a commodity
 (e.g.
 tea and carbonated drinks under beverages) can be viewed as a quantity
 of a composite good (i.e.
 beverages) along with the value consumed of a quality metric (proportion
 of tea and carbonated drinks).
 In other words, the quantity-price tuples 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1},p_{1}),(q_{2},p_{2})...$
\end_inset

 within a commodity could be expressed as a quantity and quality pair i.e.
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1},p_{1}),(q_{2},p_{2})...$
\end_inset

, we should have 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q_{G},P_{G}),(\nu_{G},p_{\nu_{G}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{G},Q_{G}$
\end_inset

 are prices and quantity consumed for a composite good while 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{G}$
\end_inset

 represents the quality of the good corresponding to the real quantities
 consumed for several items.
 If the quantities consumed are observed then this is simply a price-structure
 (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{*})$
\end_inset

 weighted sum of quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\nu_{G} & =\sum_{i\in G}(\frac{q_{i}p_{i}^{*}}{q_{G}})\label{eq:quality_def}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 represents the price-structure ratio corresponding to the item 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{G}=\sum_{j\in G}q_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that regardless of how the items are aggregated, such a formulation
 always requires the rather stringent aggregation conditions of the composite
 commodity theorem conditions to be met (see Nelson
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"

\end_inset

 and Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonEconConsumer"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
In an earlier discussion on status consumption, we have explained how the
 demanded quality could be motivated by status needs.
 It may seem apt to infer the price of quality (or status) in the market
 to view how status needs are priced.
 However our approach to interpret quality from the substitution between
 the wider commodity groups uses a relative price structure and composite
 price to achieve the same goal.
 In using a relative price structure, one does not really need the price
 of quality in the cost-function (or the budget share regression)  even
 though quality is treated as a separate commodity.
 This is because we already have a valid composite good price (base-price)
 from the real prices of the items - an aggregate price that with the relative
 price structure determines the price of quality
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
One could indeed interpret the quality in the market as the gradient of
 price of preferred items (sorted by price or otherwise).
 This too would however lead to a formulation equivalent to the aggregation
 problem.
 Consider for example that with energy, such a gradient would be calculated
 with the price one has to pay to get more of electricity.
 Similarly, for food, this would be the price one has to pay to get more
 of meat etc.
 The formulation effectively relies on the basket aggregate consumed - and
 is thus equivalent to the composite aggregated method (which in turn relies
 on a composite aggregate price).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 More specifically, if 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{G}$
\end_inset

 represents the expenditure on group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, using a constant relative price-structure allows us to write the demand
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(E_{G},p_{G})$
\end_inset

 as :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
g(E_{G},p_{G}) & \equiv g(\frac{E_{G}}{P_{G}},p_{G}^{*})\label{eq:demand_function_quality}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Let's consider an example to illustrate this better (see Nelson for a more
 detailed theoretical discussion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"

\end_inset

).
 Let's say we observe the consumption on lamb and chicken within a protein
 commodity with prices observed as 20£, 10£ (resp.) and the quantities consumed
 by the consumer are 1.5kg and 2kg (resp.).
 One approach is to the treat the physical sum of quantities i.e.
 3.5 kg as the quantity of the composite good 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

protein
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 However, it is difficult to argue that the consumers optimise the weight
 of the composite good - rather than comparing the disparate quantities
 of items (see Nelson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"

\end_inset

 for the technical details of this argument)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
If the sum of physical quantities is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{G}=\sum_{i\in G}q_{i}$
\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{G}=\frac{E_{G}}{P_{G}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{G}$
\end_inset

 is the expenditure and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{G}$
\end_inset

 is the price-index.
 The core of Nelson's argument is that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{G}=q_{G}$
\end_inset

 only if quality effects are absent since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{G}=q_{G}\Rightarrow\frac{E_{G}}{P_{G}}=\frac{E_{G}}{V_{G}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow P_{G}=V_{G}=P_{G}\nu_{G}$
\end_inset

 (unit quantity is interpreted as 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{G}=\frac{E_{G}}{q_{G}}$
\end_inset

 ).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A quality-adjusted quantity is a more appropriate formulation for this
 purpose.
 Since quality is to be priced in the market, we can consider this price-structu
red weighted quantity as the quality-adjusted quantity and express the pair
\begin_inset Formula $\{(20,1.5).(10,2)\}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $(10,4(=2\times1.5+1\times2))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1.6=\frac{4}{1.5+2})$
\end_inset

 .
  Notice that the price of the composite good is exactly zero since the
 total expenditure is already accounted for in the composite good i.e.
 10
\begin_inset Formula $\times4=40$
\end_inset

.
 If the quantities consumed were slightly different for another consumer
 e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(20,0.5),(10,3)\}$
\end_inset

 then too
\begin_inset Formula $(E=40)$
\end_inset

 and we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(10,4(=2\times0.5+1\times3))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1.14=\frac{4}{3.5})$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to see that the quality is lower for the latter case even though
 the physical quantity is the same.
 Thus, empirically quality adjusted quantity provides the total expenditure
 and there is no price needed for the quality value calculated in the above
 fashion.
 This is slightly different from the Deaton's approach - which is to view
 quality as a separate good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
It is worth emphasising that the quality metric used above is based on the
 rather stringent condition of a constant relative price structure (i.e.
 the Hicks aggregation commodity theorem).
 At a more fundamental level, quality can be aggregated only as long as
 the goods within the group can be ordered on a certain criteria.
 This order is the judgment of the researcher - not the consumer.
 For the meat commodity group, as an example, there may be no reason to
 think that goat is of higher quality than beef if the former is slightly
 costlier.
 However, quality differences are easier to explain if the price differences
 are larger - e.g.
 with the choice of pulses over chicken under the protein category.
 This judgment of quality should thus be interpreted by the researcher at
 an appropriate level of granularity.
 This is indeed a prerequisite for the quantity aggregate to make sense.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
It would appear that while such a quality metric can be used to understand
 consumption of quality, it is limited by the aggregated view that makes
 it desirable
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
Notice also that we cannot talk about the quality metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{G}$
\end_inset

 unless the quantity of consumption is observed (as if often the case with
 food).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The approaches that view a higher quality product in terms of a lower quality
 product are somewhat problematic when the items vary widely.
 The demand of a better good in a commodity group as a multiple of the worse
 good may be plausible for meat/food but considering electricity in terms
 of the coal used into one aggregate is likely to be problematic (see the
 discussion on consumer indices in Fisher-Shell 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"

\end_inset

 ).
 More fundamentally, the substitution between the choice of energy between
 kerosene and electricity is not as straightforward as between qualities
 of protein
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
For energy in the LSMS data, such a quality measure cannot be calculated
 since quantity of energy consumed (kerosene litres or electricity kWhs)
 is not recorded.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus the continuous measures make more sense in a Houthakker-like setting
 where a mixture of high and low quality items are consumed.
 In non-food categories (e.g.
 transport) the quality differences are more discrete (more so in the developing
 countries) and the consumers either consume a certain quantity of an item
 or they don't at all.
 While it is often possible to proxy such differences as regional differences,
 but the fact remains that a consumer faces a discrete choice more often
 in non-food categories.
 One therefore seek appropriate selection approaches before aggregating
 demand over such items.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
With these caveats we can attempt to explain quality changes with respect
 to changes in asset ownership, age etc.
 in a population.
 Since our wider goal is to explain status consumption using the intertemporal
 substitution and the consumer's perception of risk, we compare asset ownership
 and needs with the consumption of quality as well.
 While we do assume a weak separability of commodity groups for quantity
 - we argue that despite there being a possible inertia in doing so, the
 consumers may substitute between quality over commodity groups and assets
 owned.
 For example, rise of prices of electricity could potentially affect food
 quality - even though the quantity consumed may be limited by needs.
 An analysis of the cross-price effects i.e.
 the effect of prices of non-food items on food quality can test for this
 substitution.
 The data from possession of assets can further indicate the differences
 between asset ownership bands.
 However, in the current chapter, we have only used asset ownership as one
 of the control variables.
 A comparison of changes in asset ownership over time with changes in quality
 across several household-characteristics is to be explored in the subsequent
 chapters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
We now provide a comparison of two variants of the AIDS model used for measuring
 quality elasticities in the literature.
 We assess their relevance, shortcomings before suggesting an adaption to
 our goals.
 The first AIDS variant (McKelvey 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"

\end_inset

) uses a continuous measure of quality (as defined above) - except for electrici
ty (which is simply an indicator variable).
 Asset ownership also appears as indicator variables in this method.
 In the second variant, an instrument variable approach is used (Heien-Wessells
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HeienWessellsAIDSCensored1990"

\end_inset

).
 We argue in favour of a discrete method - which we believe would make more
 sense in the conspicuous consumption contexts - particularly due to the
 relevance of asset ownership.
 A cross-section analysis of quality and assets purchased is then provided
 to motivate the needs for discrete modeling of choice.
\end_layout

